T1  - Franchise turnover and failure: New research and perspectives
AU  - Holmberg, Stevan R.
AU  - Morgan, Kathryn Boe
JO  - Journal of Business Venturing
VL  - 18
IS  - 3
SP  - 403
EP  - 418
PY  - 2003
DA  - 2003/05/01/
SN  - 0883-9026
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/S0883-9026(02)00085-X
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S088390260200085X
AB  - Entrepreneurship literature has long noted likely significant new venture failure rates. This paper's new franchise failure concept reconciles many prior, seemingly inconsistent study results based largely on franchisor's surveys. Data include more than 800 franchise systems and 250,000 franchise outlets over four consecutive years and are based on state-required Uniform Franchise Offering Circular (UFOC) registration data. Overall franchisee turnover rates are significant and appear to have increased. The result is a 1997 median franchisee turnover with a transfer rate of 10.49% (8.86% in 1994). Franchisee failure and turnover are important areas that merit further study and analysis.
